values:
Never thought I&#39;d say this but I&#39;m actually feeling lost from not having the need to study. I don&#39;t (need to) bring work home with me on a daily basis because let&#39;s face it where am I working at, and on the nights where I don&#39;t meet up with friends I basically come home and find myself with nothing to do.&nbsp;

So recently I took up baking. And while I&#39;ve had some minor successes (banana bread and chocolate cupcakes) I hope to try baking some more higher level food- think macaroons, and maybe salted caramel cupcakes. Maybe I can open my own cafe one day with friends!

Also I don&#39;t ever think I&#39;ll do gelish nails anymore. They&#39;re adorable and endure well but I&#39;m a cheapo who refuses to pay extra for the removal. And because the first and only time I did gelish manicure the manicurist cut my cuticles and made it bleed.&nbsp;

I got a job. I&#39;m satisfied with the pay, and I know I will have the work-life balance I always wanted :)

Awhile ago, I told the people in my cca that when I score 240 points at 70m (the furthest distance a female archer can go), I will have finished my archery &quot;game&quot; and be able to graduate knowing that I have accomplished what I set out for. Yesterday, I scored 245 points :)&nbsp;

This is the first time in my entire 4 years that I&#39;m still going for training on week 12-13. I have a competition on week 13. Hell weeks? Not this sem.&nbsp;

I&#39;m actually having a great semester. I put archery first, friends second, and studies last. And things are turning out great for me.&nbsp;

Why didn&#39;t I do this before??&nbsp;

So after staying in school from 8.30am to 5am on Monday rushing for my project presentation and report, I&#39;ve been experiencing stress and fatigue in the form of dull headaches. Add that to heartburns. Add that to studying for the final &quot;quiz&quot;, a 40% of the total grade affair.&nbsp;

Can I drink coffee, pop Panadols, antacids, drink banana milk all at once?&nbsp;

This semester needs to end.&nbsp;

December to-do list:&nbsp;

Look through my transcript and write down the following things for every single module I took in SMU
&nbsp; 1. Best memory of module
&nbsp; 2. Worst memory of module
&nbsp; 3. What I learnt from module/professor/groupmates&nbsp;

That ought to be interesting.&nbsp;

Playing slow songs and studying makes me think of the trip I took to Merida during my exchange.&nbsp;

We went to this town very rich in history- the streets were all one way and cobblestoned, the buildings on the streets were one to three storeys high, and square, with flat roofs. So corners were extremely sharp and pathways were extremely narrow. During the day the streets were extremely crowded. Yet at night the streets became empty, I wonder where all the people went.&nbsp;

Every trip I took, I remembered vividly at least one particular moment of it. Listening to my friends on exchange now, I can relate to them, but now I feel helpless. I just wish they&#39;ll all feel better soon.&nbsp;
